how your parents met.

718
01:15:04,733 --> 01:15:06,564
They met at Auburn.

719
01:15:06,735 --> 01:15:10,603
What about the details?
How they fell in love.

720
01:15:10,772 --> 01:15:12,706
The circus. The war.

721
01:15:12,875 --> 01:15:14,775
You never told me any of that.

722
01:15:14,943 --> 01:15:17,104
That's because most of it
never happened.

723
01:15:18,947 --> 01:15:21,177
But it's romantic.

724
01:15:24,586 --> 01:15:27,146
-What?
-What, I know better...

725
01:15:27,322 --> 01:15:30,485
...than to argue romance
with a French woman.

726
01:15:32,227 --> 01:15:34,218
Do you love your father?

727
01:15:34,396 --> 01:15:37,991
Everyone loves my father.
He's a very likable guy.

728
01:15:39,368 --> 01:15:40,926
Do you love him?

729
01:15:46,074 --> 01:15:48,065
You have to understand.

730
01:15:48,243 --> 01:15:52,009
When I was growing up,
he was gone more than he was there.

731
01:15:52,180 --> 01:15:56,139
And I started thinking maybe he's got
this second life somewhere else.

732
01:15:57,052 --> 01:15:59,782
Another family, another house.

733
01:15:59,955 --> 01:16:03,254
And he leaves us
and goes to them.

734
01:16:03,425 --> 01:16:05,052
Or, or....

735
01:16:07,462 --> 01:16:11,558
Or maybe there is no second family.
Maybe he never wanted a family.

736
01:16:12,601 --> 01:16:17,197
Whatever it is, he likes his second life
better and he tells his stories...

737
01:16:17,372 --> 01:16:19,863
...because he can't stand
this boring place.

738
01:16:20,042 --> 01:16:23,136
-But it's not true.
-Well, what's true?

739
01:16:25,213 --> 01:16:28,011
He's never told me
a single true thing.

740
01:16:29,952 --> 01:16:31,476
Look, hey....

741
01:16:32,888 --> 01:16:35,686
I know why you like him.

742
01:16:35,857 --> 01:16:38,621
I know why everyone likes him.

743
01:16:39,761 --> 01:16:43,060
But I need you to tell me
that I'm not crazy.

744
01:16:43,231 --> 01:16:46,132
Oh, you're not.

745
01:16:48,136 --> 01:16:50,832
And I think you should talk to him.

746
01:16:56,044 --> 01:16:59,207
Larry Puckett's Chevrolet
lets the customer do the talking.

747
01:16:59,381 --> 01:17:03,044
Larry Puckett's GM-certified vehicles
are under factory warranty.

748
01:17:03,218 --> 01:17:07,245
And you can save up to 40 percent
off the original MSRP.

749
01:17:07,422 --> 01:17:10,118
-Did I ever tell you about--?
-Yes.

750
01:17:11,360 --> 01:17:14,796
The maple tree and the Buick?
We've heard it.

751
01:17:17,232 --> 01:17:20,724
I know someone who hasn't.

752
01:17:20,902 --> 01:17:24,531
-The--
-Tree fell on the car, spilling the syrup.

753
01:17:24,706 --> 01:17:28,233
Which attracted the flies,
which got stuck to it...

754
01:17:28,410 --> 01:17:31,470
...and flew off with the whole car.

755
01:17:35,984 --> 01:17:39,442
But the real story
is how I got the car.

756
01:17:39,621 --> 01:17:41,316
-You see--
-Dad?

757
01:17:41,490 --> 01:17:42,957
Son.

758
01:17:43,125 --> 01:17:45,150
Can we talk?

759
01:17:47,596 --> 01:17:50,030
I think I'll get started
on these dishes.

760
01:17:50,198 --> 01:17:52,393
I'll help you.

761
01:18:07,949 --> 01:18:11,282
-You know about icebergs, Dad?
-Do l?

762
01:18:11,453 --> 01:18:13,887
I saw an iceberg once.

763
01:18:14,056 --> 01:18:17,355
They were hauling it down to Texas
for drinking water.

764
01:18:17,526 --> 01:18:21,587
They didn't count on there being
an elephant frozen inside.

765
01:18:21,763 --> 01:18:24,561
-The woolly kind. A mammoth.
-Dad!

766
01:18:24,733 --> 01:18:26,701
What?

767
01:18:28,503 --> 01:18:30,698
I'm trying to make a metaphor here.

768
01:18:30,872 --> 01:18:33,568
Well, you shouldn't have started
with a question...

769
01:18:33,742 --> 01:18:36,040
...because people
want to answer questions.

770
01:18:36,211 --> 01:18:39,806
You should've started with,
"The thing about icebergs is...."

771
01:18:39,981 --> 01:18:43,417
Okay, okay. The thing about
icebergs is you only see 1 0 percent.

772
01:18:43,585 --> 01:18:46,986
The other 90 percent is below
the water where you can't see it.

773
01:18:47,155 --> 01:18:49,214
And that's...

774
01:18:49,391 --> 01:18:52,155
...what it is with you, Dad.

775
01:18:52,327 --> 01:18:55,057
I am only seeing this little bit...

776
01:18:55,230 --> 01:18:57,061
...that sticks above the water.

777
01:18:57,232 --> 01:19:00,395
Oh, you're only seeing down
to my nose? My chin? My--

778
01:19:00,569 --> 01:19:03,504
Dad, I have no idea who you are...

779
01:19:03,672 --> 01:19:06,903
...because you've never told me
a single fact.

780
01:19:07,075 --> 01:19:11,341
I've told you a thousand facts, Will.
That's what I do, I tell stories!

781
01:19:11,513 --> 01:19:14,744
You tell...Iies, Dad.

782
01:19:14,916 --> 01:19:16,247
You tell amusing lies.

783
01:19:16,418 --> 01:19:19,512
Stories are what you tell
a 5-year-old at bedtime.

784
01:19:19,688 --> 01:19:22,555
They're not elaborate mythologies
that you maintain...

785
01:19:22,724 --> 01:19:25,158
...when your son is 1 0 and 1 5
and 20 and 30.

786
01:19:25,327 --> 01:19:28,194
And I believed you.

787
01:19:29,965 --> 01:19:33,401
I believed your stories
so much longer than I should have.

788
01:19:33,568 --> 01:19:36,662
Then when I realized
everything you said was impossible...

789
01:19:36,838 --> 01:19:39,068
...I felt like a fool
to have trusted you.

790
01:19:39,241 --> 01:19:41,505
You're like Santa Claus
and the Easter Bunny.

791
01:19:41,676 --> 01:19:43,507
Just as charming and just as fake.

792
01:19:43,678 --> 01:19:45,908
You think I'm fake.

793
01:19:47,382 --> 01:19:51,512
Only on the surface, Dad.
But it's all I've ever seen.

794
01:19:53,288 --> 01:19:54,949
Look.

795
01:19:56,525 --> 01:19:58,959
I'm about to have...

796
01:19:59,461 --> 01:20:00,689
...a kid of my own.

797
01:20:00,862 --> 01:20:03,558
It would kill me
if he went through his whole life...

798
01:20:03,732 --> 01:20:05,791
...never understanding me.

799
01:20:05,967 --> 01:20:08,401
It would kill you, huh?

800
01:20:10,372 --> 01:20:13,899
What do you want, Will?
Who do you want me to be?

801
01:20:14,075 --> 01:20:15,736
Just yourself.

802
01:20:15,911 --> 01:20:19,711
Good, bad, everything.
Just show me who you are for once.

803
01:20:19,881 --> 01:20:22,975
I've been nothing but myself
since the day I was born.

804
01:20:23,151 --> 01:20:27,679
And if you can't see that,
it's your failing, not mine!

805
01:20:59,020 --> 01:21:03,582
Your father decided
that he needed to have an office...

806
01:21:03,758 --> 01:21:06,852
...and, of course, it wouldn't do
to have it in the house.

807
01:21:07,028 --> 01:21:08,552
So....

808
01:21:10,198 --> 01:21:13,929
You'll know better than me
what's important.

809
01:21:25,247 --> 01:21:27,374
What is it?

810
01:21:28,817 --> 01:21:30,808
It was during the war.

811
01:21:30,986 --> 01:21:34,854
Your father went missing.
They thought he was dead.

812
01:21:36,057 --> 01:21:38,457
Oh, that really happened?

813
01:21:38,627 --> 01:21:42,393
Not everything your father says
is a complete fabrication.

814
01:21:43,732 --> 01:21:46,758
I think I'll go check on him.

815
01:21:48,937 --> 01:21:51,599
I need to lie down for a bit.

816
01:21:51,773 --> 01:21:54,401
Okay, go.

817
01:22:09,190 --> 01:22:13,957
After the war, the sons of Alabama
returned home, looking for work.

818
01:22:14,129 --> 01:22:15,892
Each had the advantage over me.

819
01:22:16,064 --> 01:22:19,625
They were alive,
while I was officially deceased.

820
01:22:19,801 --> 01:22:21,564
With my prospects few...

821
01:22:21,736 --> 01:22:25,536
...I took a job as a traveling salesman.
It suited me.

822
01:22:25,707 --> 01:22:28,835
If there was one thing
you can say about Edward Bloom...

823
01:22:29,010 --> 01:22:31,240
...it's that I am a social person.

824
01:22:31,947 --> 01:22:35,348
-Congratulations.
-Thank you, sir.

825
01:22:36,017 --> 01:22:38,611
I could be gone
for weeks at a time.

826
01:22:38,787 --> 01:22:41,722
But every other Friday,
I put all the money I made...

827
01:22:41,890 --> 01:22:45,519
...into an account set aside
for a proper house...

828
01:22:45,694 --> 01:22:47,889
...with a white picket fence.

829
01:22:53,668 --> 01:22:57,195
I'd like a moment of your time
to tell you about my new product...

830
01:22:57,372 --> 01:22:59,704
...the Handi-matic.

831
01:23:15,190 --> 01:23:18,489
A few years later, I added
other products and other cities...

832
01:23:18,660 --> 01:23:22,221
...until my territory stretched from
the coast to western Texas.

833
01:23:47,088 --> 01:23:48,578
Edward?

834
01:23:48,757 --> 01:23:50,384
Edward Bloom!

835
01:23:50,558 --> 01:23:52,185
It's me, Norther Winslow.

836
01:23:52,360 --> 01:23:54,225
I don't believe it.

837
01:23:54,396 --> 01:23:58,696
I was astonished to see the greatest
poet of both Ashton and Spectre...

838
01:23:58,867 --> 01:24:00,767
...all the way out in Texas.

839
01:24:00,935 --> 01:24:04,803
I want you to know, when you left
Spectre, it opened my eyes.

840
01:24:04,973 --> 01:24:08,636
There was a whole life out there
that I was not living.

841
01:24:08,810 --> 01:24:10,300
So I traveled.

842
01:24:10,478 --> 01:24:13,641
I saw France, Africa,
half of South America.

843
01:24:13,815 --> 01:24:16,443
Every day, a new adventure.
That's my motto.

844
01:24:16,618 --> 01:24:18,779
That's great, Norther.
I'm happy for you.

845
01:24:18,953 --> 01:24:21,217
What are you doing now?

846
01:24:22,323 --> 01:24:23,950
I'm robbing this place.

847
01:24:27,996 --> 01:24:29,964
All right, everybody down!

848
01:24:31,433 --> 01:24:34,698
Hey!
Just slide that over.

849
01:24:40,909 --> 01:24:43,673
-Would you mind grabbing that?
-What?

850
01:24:44,112 --> 01:24:45,602
The gun.

851
01:24:47,115 --> 01:24:49,549
I'm gonna be cleaning out
the cash drawers...

852
01:24:49,717 --> 01:24:53,915
...and my associate here
is gonna handle the vault.

853
01:24:59,928 --> 01:25:03,386
All right, you!
You help my friend, okay?

854
01:25:04,199 --> 01:25:05,860
Let's go!

855
01:25:25,520 --> 01:25:27,454
I'm sorry, ma'am.
I am.

856
01:25:27,622 --> 01:25:30,750
I really just don't want anyone
to get hurt.

857
01:25:30,925 --> 01:25:32,859
It's not that.

858
01:25:33,828 --> 01:25:35,762
It's just....

859
01:25:41,236 --> 01:25:42,828
There's no money.

860
01:25:43,638 --> 01:25:47,506
We're completely bankrupt.
Don't tell anybody.

861
01:25:47,675 --> 01:25:51,668
It turned out that the Savings & Loan
had already been robbed...

862
01:25:51,846 --> 01:25:56,340
...not by armed bandits, but
by speculators in Texas real estate.

863
01:25:56,518 --> 01:25:58,509
All right, let's go!

864
01:26:09,697 --> 01:26:11,722
Norther!

865
01:26:31,352 --> 01:26:34,116
Yeah! There's gotta be
close to $400 here!

866
01:26:34,289 --> 01:26:36,780
And that's just from the drawers.

867
01:26:36,958 --> 01:26:39,426
Let's see what you got
from the vault.

868
01:26:49,337 --> 01:26:51,931
This is it? The whole vault?

869
01:26:52,106 --> 01:26:54,472
I'm afraid so.

870
01:26:57,212 --> 01:26:59,146
It's got your deposit slip on it.

871
01:26:59,314 --> 01:27:02,181
Well, I just didn't want you
leaving empty-handed.

872
01:27:02,350 --> 01:27:06,116
There's something you should know.
The reason they don't have money....

873
01:27:06,287 --> 01:27:09,552
I told Norther about
the vagaries of Texas oil money...

874
01:27:09,724 --> 01:27:12,591
...and its effect on real-estate prices...

875
01:27:12,760 --> 01:27:15,923
...and how lax enforcement
of fiduciary process...

876
01:27:16,097 --> 01:27:19,897
...had made savings and loans
particularly vulnerable.

877
01:27:20,068 --> 01:27:24,869
Hearing this news,
Norther was left with one conclusion:

878
01:27:25,039 --> 01:27:28,236
I should go to Wall Street.
That's where all the money is.

879
01:27:28,409 --> 01:27:32,004
I knew then that while my days
as a criminal were over...

880
01:27:32,180 --> 01:27:33,442
Thanks for the hand!

881
01:27:33,615 --> 01:27:35,606
...Norther's were just beginning.

882
01:27:35,783 --> 01:27:38,217
When Norther made
his first million dollars...

883
01:27:38,386 --> 01:27:40,650
...he sent me a check for 10,000.

884
01:27:40,822 --> 01:27:44,918
I protested, but he said it was my fee
as his career advisor.

885
01:27:45,093 --> 01:27:48,256
It was enough to buy my wife
a proper house...

886
01:27:48,429 --> 01:27:50,488
... with a white picket fence.

887
01:27:50,665 --> 01:27:54,863
And for that, it was all the riches
a man could ever want.

888
01:28:28,736 --> 01:28:30,670
I was drying out.

889
01:28:32,440 --> 01:28:34,340
I see.

890
01:28:36,511 --> 01:28:40,709
I think we ought to get you
a plant mister...

891
01:28:40,882 --> 01:28:43,680
...so we can just spray you
like a fern.

892
01:29:09,610 --> 01:29:12,078
Come, now.

893
01:29:16,417 --> 01:29:19,818
I don't think I'll ever dry out.

894
01:30:18,012 --> 01:30:21,038
You carry on. I'll see....

895
01:30:25,720 --> 01:30:27,517
Hello.

896
01:30:28,089 --> 01:30:32,025
-Are you Jennifer Hill?
-I am.

897
01:30:32,193 --> 01:30:34,354
And you're Will.

898
01:30:34,529 --> 01:30:37,498
I've seen a picture of you.
That's how I recognize you.

899
01:30:40,201 --> 01:30:42,863
Listen, Kenny,
why don't we skip the lesson today?

900
01:30:43,037 --> 01:30:45,335
We can go again next week.

901
01:30:45,506 --> 01:30:47,531
Do I have to give it back to my mom?

902
01:30:47,708 --> 01:30:50,268
Well, I won't tell her if you won't.

903
01:31:01,722 --> 01:31:03,189
How did you know my father?

904
01:31:03,591 --> 01:31:05,650
Well, this was on his sales route...

905
01:31:05,827 --> 01:31:09,888
...so he was through here all the time,
and everyone in town knew him.

906
01:31:10,064 --> 01:31:12,123
Were you having an affair?

907
01:31:14,535 --> 01:31:16,969
Wow. Wow, you just said it.

908
01:31:17,772 --> 01:31:21,401
I was expecting to dance
around this for another half-hour.

909
01:31:23,211 --> 01:31:26,237
I've seen him with women.
He flirts. He always has.

910
01:31:26,414 --> 01:31:30,544
And on some level,
I just presumed that he was...

911
01:31:30,718 --> 01:31:34,245
...cheating on my mom.
I just never had proof.

912
01:31:36,924 --> 01:31:38,824
Well, can I ask you a question?

913
01:31:38,993 --> 01:31:41,723
If you found this deed,
why didn't you just ask Eddie?

914
01:31:42,864 --> 01:31:45,196
Because he's dying.

915
01:31:53,908 --> 01:31:58,572
Look, I don't know how much
you want to know about any of this.

916
01:31:58,746 --> 01:32:00,873
You have one image of your father...

917
01:32:01,048 --> 01:32:03,312
...and it'd be wrong of me
to change it...

918
01:32:03,484 --> 01:32:05,418
...especially this late in the game.

919
01:32:05,686 --> 01:32:08,052
My father talked about things
he never did...

920
01:32:08,222 --> 01:32:11,589
...and I'm sure he did a lot of things
that he never talked about.

921
01:32:11,759 --> 01:32:13,784
I'm just trying to reconcile the two.

922
01:32:17,231 --> 01:32:20,325
The first thing
you have to understand...

923
01:32:20,501 --> 01:32:23,470
...is that your father
never meant to end up here.

924
01:32:24,038 --> 01:32:25,403
Yet he did.

925
01:32:25,606 --> 01:32:27,301
Twice.

926
01:32:27,842 --> 01:32:30,333
The first time, he was early.

927
01:32:30,511 --> 01:32:32,741
The second time, he was late.

928
01:32:34,849 --> 01:32:38,751
Those days, your father was working
for himself.

929
01:32:38,920 --> 01:32:41,855
If there's one thing you could
say about Edward Bloom...

930
01:32:42,023 --> 01:32:47,017
...it's that he was a social person,
and people took a liking to him.

931
01:32:47,194 --> 01:32:50,425
One night, he was returning
from three weeks on the road...

932
01:32:50,598 --> 01:32:54,295
... when he hit a thunderstorm
unlike any in his life.

933
01:34:42,610 --> 01:34:45,135
Fate has a way of circling back
on a man...

934
01:34:45,312 --> 01:34:47,405
...and taking him by surprise.

935
01:34:52,153 --> 01:34:55,816
A man sees things differently
at different times in his life.

936
01:34:55,990 --> 01:34:59,926
This town didn't seem the same
now that he was older.

937
01:35:01,128 --> 01:35:04,655
A new road had brought
the outside world to Spectre...

938
01:35:04,832 --> 01:35:07,960
...and with it, banks, liens and debt.

939
01:35:08,135 --> 01:35:12,970
Almost everywhere you looked,
people were bankrupt.

940
01:35:14,241 --> 01:35:17,608
The auction today
is for the town of Spectre.

941
01:35:17,778 --> 01:35:20,508
-The opening bid will be $1 0,000.
-So Edward Bloom...

942
01:35:20,681 --> 01:35:23,309
-...decided to buy the town.
-50,000.

943
01:35:27,488 --> 01:35:30,685
-I couldn't believe my eyes--
-He was never a wealthy man...

944
01:35:30,858 --> 01:35:36,023
...but he had made other men rich,
and now he asked for their favors.

945
01:35:37,932 --> 01:35:40,958
-I'm trying to save....
-Most of them hadn't seen Spectre.

946
01:35:41,135 --> 01:35:44,366
They only had Edward's words
to describe it.

947
01:35:44,538 --> 01:35:47,837
That's all he needed.
He sold them on the dream.

948
01:35:48,242 --> 01:35:50,733
So first he bought the farms.

949
01:35:50,911 --> 01:35:54,813
Then he bought the houses.
And then he bought the stores.

950
01:35:55,416 --> 01:36:00,513
Whatever he bought, the people were
not asked to leave or pay rent.

951
01:36:00,688 --> 01:36:03,589
They were just asked to keep
doing as they were doing.

952
01:36:03,958 --> 01:36:07,985
In that way, he could make sure
the town would never die.

953
01:36:10,431 --> 01:36:15,698
Within six months, his trust had
purchased the entire town.

954
01:36:15,870 --> 01:36:18,532
With one exception.

955
01:36:42,763 --> 01:36:45,823
You must be Edward Bloom.

956
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:47,297
How do you know?

957
01:36:47,902 --> 01:36:50,598
No one would come out here
unless they had business.

958
01:36:50,805 --> 01:36:53,797
And no one would have business
with me except for you.

959
01:36:53,974 --> 01:36:56,340
You're buying the town.

960
01:36:56,844 --> 01:37:00,871
Apparently I overlooked this one
piece of it, and I'd like to remedy that.

961
01:37:01,482 --> 01:37:06,385
In order for the town to be preserved,
the trust must own it, in its entirety.

962
01:37:06,554 --> 01:37:07,919
And so I've heard.

963
01:37:08,088 --> 01:37:11,546
I'll offer you more than it's worth.
And you won't have to move.

964
01:37:11,725 --> 01:37:15,161
Nothing will change except the name
on the deed, you have my word.

965
01:37:15,329 --> 01:37:17,991
Now, let me get this straight.

966
01:37:18,165 --> 01:37:20,827
You buy the swamp from me,
but I'll stay in it?

967
01:37:21,001 --> 01:37:23,663
You'll own the house,
but it'll still be mine?

968
01:37:23,838 --> 01:37:27,831
I'll be here, and you'll come and go as
you please to one place or another.

969
01:37:28,008 --> 01:37:29,976
Do I have that right?

970
01:37:30,144 --> 01:37:32,738
In so many words, yes.

971
01:37:33,614 --> 01:37:35,582
Yeah, then I don't think so,
Mr. Bloom.

972
01:37:36,250 --> 01:37:39,276
If nothing's gonna change,
I'd just as soon it not change...

973
01:37:39,453 --> 01:37:42,422
...in the way things haven't been
changing all this time.

974
01:37:43,657 --> 01:37:48,424
It's not like you'll lose anything.
You can ask anyone in town.

975
01:37:49,830 --> 01:37:52,321
Why are you buying this land,
Mr. Bloom?

976
01:37:52,499 --> 01:37:54,057
Some sort of midlife crisis?

977
01:37:54,835 --> 01:37:57,599
Instead of buying a convertible,
you buy a town?

978
01:37:58,072 --> 01:38:00,233
Helping people makes me happy.

979
01:38:00,941 --> 01:38:04,104
I'm not convinced
you should be happy.

980
01:38:04,278 --> 01:38:08,237
-I'm sorry. Have I offended you?
-No.

981
01:38:08,415 --> 01:38:10,315
You did exactly what you promised.

982
01:38:10,951 --> 01:38:15,581
You came back.
I was just expecting you sooner.

983
01:38:23,130 --> 01:38:24,722
You're Beamen's daughter.

984
01:38:26,533 --> 01:38:29,263
Your name's different.
Did you get married?

985
01:38:30,004 --> 01:38:35,067
I was 1 8. He was 28.
Turns out that was a big difference.

986
01:38:44,685 --> 01:38:47,950
I won't be selling you this house,
Mr. Bloom.

987
01:38:48,856 --> 01:38:50,585
I see.

988
01:38:51,592 --> 01:38:53,992
Well, thank you for your time.

989
01:39:05,239 --> 01:39:08,367
-It's stuck.
-Yeah.

990
01:39:18,652 --> 01:39:21,712
-Oh, I'm so sorry! I--
-It's okay. Just leave it.

991
01:39:21,889 --> 01:39:24,380
-No, I'll--
-Please! Just go.

992
01:39:25,926 --> 01:39:28,486
-But--
-Go.

993
01:39:30,798 --> 01:39:35,565
Most men in that situation would
accept their failure and move on.

994
01:39:35,736 --> 01:39:37,805
But Edward was not like most men.

995
01:39:37,805 --> 01:39:38,794
But Edward was not like most men.

996
01:39:48,148 --> 01:39:49,581
Hold!

997
01:39:53,020 --> 01:39:55,853
They both had completely
different characters but...

998
01:39:56,023 --> 01:39:58,719
...well, just one pair of legs.

999
01:40:09,069 --> 01:40:12,630
As the months passed, he found
more and more things to fix...

1000
01:40:12,806 --> 01:40:16,708
...until the shack no longer
resembled itself.

1001
01:40:32,926 --> 01:40:36,953
Of course, the best part
was coming up with the new material.

1002
01:40:37,731 --> 01:40:40,199
By the time the twins and l
had got to Havana...

1003
01:40:40,367 --> 01:40:45,964
...we'd worked out a new routine,
using only a ukulele and a harmonica.

1004
01:41:05,259 --> 01:41:08,820
-Well....
-You could leave it there.

1005
01:41:26,346 --> 01:41:27,938
No.

1006
01:41:38,025 --> 01:41:39,959
Now, don't.

1007
01:41:40,127 --> 01:41:45,292
Don't be embarrassed. I should never
have let you think that....

1008
01:41:46,133 --> 01:41:48,931
I'm in love with my wife.

1009
01:41:49,937 --> 01:41:51,928
Yeah, I know.

1010
01:41:52,106 --> 01:41:55,234
And from the first day I saw her
until the day I die...

1011
01:41:55,409 --> 01:41:57,468
...she's the only one.

1012
01:41:58,212 --> 01:42:00,146
Lucky girl.

1013
01:42:01,181 --> 01:42:04,116
I'm sorry, Jenny. I am.

1014
01:42:12,025 --> 01:42:14,323
Wait! Edward.

1015
01:42:55,903 --> 01:42:58,804
One day, Edward Bloom left...

1016
01:42:58,972 --> 01:43:02,806
...and never returned
to the town he'd saved.

1017
01:43:15,355 --> 01:43:17,186
As for the girl...

1018
01:43:17,357 --> 01:43:20,053
...the common belief
was that she'd become a witch...

1019
01:43:20,227 --> 01:43:22,627
...and crazy at that.

1020
01:43:24,064 --> 01:43:27,522
She became something
of a legend herself.

1021
01:43:28,802 --> 01:43:33,205
And the story ended where it began.

1022
01:43:34,341 --> 01:43:37,242
Logically, you couldn't be
the witch, because she was...

1023
01:43:37,411 --> 01:43:38,708
...old when he was young.

1024
01:43:39,012 --> 01:43:42,140
Well, it's logical if you think
like your father.

1025
01:43:43,116 --> 01:43:46,984
See, to him there's only
two women:

1026
01:43:47,154 --> 01:43:48,746
Your mother...

1027
01:43:48,922 --> 01:43:50,287
...and everyone else.

1028
01:43:50,557 --> 01:43:52,457
And one day...

1029
01:43:52,626 --> 01:43:57,086
...I realized I was in love with a man
who could never love me back.

1030
01:43:58,131 --> 01:44:00,292
I was living in a fairy tale.

1031
01:44:01,435 --> 01:44:03,767
I'm not sure I should've told you
any of this.

1032
01:44:03,937 --> 01:44:06,462
No, no, no, I wanted to know. I'm....

1033
01:44:06,640 --> 01:44:08,107
I'm glad I know.

1034
01:44:08,809 --> 01:44:12,142
I wanted to be as important to him
as you were.

1035
01:44:12,646 --> 01:44:14,443
And I'm....

1036
01:44:14,915 --> 01:44:16,314
I was never gonna be.

1037
01:44:19,286 --> 01:44:21,447
I was make-believe.

1038
01:44:22,923 --> 01:44:27,292
And his other life, you....

1039
01:44:28,128 --> 01:44:29,686
You were real.

1040
01:44:53,987 --> 01:44:55,579
Mom?

1041
01:44:56,623 --> 01:44:58,454
Josephine?

1042
01:45:00,294 --> 01:45:02,159
Josephine?

1043
01:45:15,809 --> 01:45:17,868
Will!

1044
01:45:19,012 --> 01:45:20,240
What happened?

1045
01:45:20,414 --> 01:45:22,177
Your father had a stroke.

1046
01:45:22,349 --> 01:45:25,477
He's upstairs with your mom
and Dr. Bennett.

1047
01:45:25,652 --> 01:45:26,983
Is he gonna be okay?

1048
01:45:34,928 --> 01:45:37,021
I don't suppose that I could...

1049
01:45:37,197 --> 01:45:39,688
...stay here with him.
I mean, in case....

1050
01:45:40,534 --> 01:45:43,469
In case he wakes up,
I really ought to be here.

1051
01:45:43,637 --> 01:45:44,899
I'll stay.

1052
01:45:45,939 --> 01:45:48,965
Why don't you go home with
Josephine. I'll stay tonight.

1053
01:45:50,811 --> 01:45:53,780
-ls that okay?
-Fine.

1054
01:45:56,683 --> 01:45:59,584
Will, you'll call if there's any...?

1055
01:45:59,753 --> 01:46:02,881
I will. I will. I'll call.

1056
01:46:04,458 --> 01:46:08,451
-Do you want some time with Dad?
-Yes. Thank you.

1057
01:47:12,559 --> 01:47:16,086
Glad to see you're not trying
to have a heartfelt talk.

1058
01:47:19,266 --> 01:47:21,860
One of my greatest
annoyances is when...

1059
01:47:22,035 --> 01:47:24,970
...people try to talk to those
who can't hear them.

1060
01:47:25,138 --> 01:47:27,265
Well, we have an advantage.

1061
01:47:27,441 --> 01:47:29,875
My father and I never talk.

1062
01:47:36,416 --> 01:47:39,476
Your father ever tell you
about the day you were born?

1063
01:47:39,653 --> 01:47:43,089
Yeah, a thousand times.
He caught an uncatchable fish.

1064
01:47:43,256 --> 01:47:47,215
Not that. The real story.
He ever tell you that?

1065
01:47:47,394 --> 01:47:49,225
No.

1066
01:47:49,396 --> 01:47:52,854
Well, your mother came in about
3 in the afternoon.

1067
01:47:53,033 --> 01:47:57,493
Her neighbor drove her, on account of
your father was away on business...

1068
01:47:57,671 --> 01:47:59,332
...in Wichita.

1069
01:47:59,506 --> 01:48:03,840
You were born a week early,
but there were no complications.

1070
01:48:04,010 --> 01:48:09,676
It was a perfect delivery.
Your father was sorry not to be there.

1071
01:48:10,217 --> 01:48:14,950
But it wasn't the custom then for men
to be in the room for deliveries...

1072
01:48:15,121 --> 01:48:19,387
...so I can't see how it would've been
much different had he been there.

1073
01:48:19,559 --> 01:48:22,323
And that's the real story
of how you were born.

1074
01:48:22,963 --> 01:48:25,397
Not very exciting, is it?

1075
01:48:25,565 --> 01:48:29,433
And I suppose if I had to choose
between the true version...

1076
01:48:29,603 --> 01:48:34,131
...and an elaborate one involving
a fish and a wedding ring...

1077
01:48:34,307 --> 01:48:36,275
...I might choose the fancy version.

1078
01:48:36,977 --> 01:48:38,945
But, then that's just me.

1079
01:48:40,013 --> 01:48:41,537
I kind of liked your version.

1080
01:49:04,104 --> 01:49:05,696
Dad?

1081
01:49:07,841 --> 01:49:11,402
Hey, Dad? Hey, you want me
to get the nurse?

1082
01:49:13,280 --> 01:49:16,340
What do you want? What can I do?
What can I get?

1083
01:49:16,516 --> 01:49:18,575
You want some water?

1084
01:49:19,653 --> 01:49:21,143
You want a bit of water?

1085
01:49:24,057 --> 01:49:26,753
The river.

1086
01:49:28,295 --> 01:49:30,160
The river?

1087
01:49:30,630 --> 01:49:34,828
Tell me how it happens.

1088
01:49:36,703 --> 01:49:38,637
How what happens?

1089
01:49:39,673 --> 01:49:42,107
How I go.

1090
01:49:46,479 --> 01:49:48,947
You mean what you saw in The Eye?

1091
01:50:02,963 --> 01:50:06,296
I don't know that story, Dad.
You never told me that one.

1092
01:50:09,169 --> 01:50:12,229
Okay. Hey, okay, I'll try.

1093
01:50:12,405 --> 01:50:15,033
I need your help.
Tell me how it starts.

1094
01:50:17,277 --> 01:50:20,940
Like this.

1095
01:50:21,114 --> 01:50:23,139
Okay. Okay.

1096
01:50:25,785 --> 01:50:29,243
Okay, so it's in the morning...

1097
01:50:29,422 --> 01:50:33,518
...and you and I are in the hospital,
and I've fallen asleep. And I wake up...

1098
01:50:33,994 --> 01:50:37,395
...and I see you,
and somehow you're better.

1099
01:50:37,564 --> 01:50:38,656
Dad?

1100
01:50:38,832 --> 01:50:40,857
You're different.

1101
01:50:41,768 --> 01:50:44,760
-Dad.
-Let's get out of here.

1102
01:50:44,938 --> 01:50:46,200
Then I say:

1103
01:50:46,373 --> 01:50:47,806
Dad, you're in no condition--

1104
01:50:47,974 --> 01:50:50,374
Get that wheelchair.

1105
01:50:52,812 --> 01:50:54,712
Hurry up! We haven't much time!

1106
01:50:54,881 --> 01:50:57,349
Once we get off this floor,
we're in the clear.

1107
01:50:57,517 --> 01:50:59,212
And we get in the wheelchair...

1108
01:50:59,386 --> 01:51:02,753
-Faster!
-...Iike we're escaping the hospital.

1109
01:51:02,922 --> 01:51:04,719
What are you doing?

1110
01:51:04,924 --> 01:51:07,256
We pass Dr. Bennett,
who tries to slow us down.

1111
01:51:07,427 --> 01:51:10,396
-Stop them!
-We're flying down the hall.

1112
01:51:10,563 --> 01:51:12,497
Orderly after orderly is chasing us.

1113
01:51:12,666 --> 01:51:14,725
Mom and Josephine
are at the end.

1114
01:51:14,901 --> 01:51:17,665
No time to explain! Stall them!

1115
01:51:23,343 --> 01:51:25,368
We come flying out
over the curb...

1116
01:51:25,545 --> 01:51:29,914
...and your old red Charger is there.
But it's new. Brand-new.

1117
01:51:30,083 --> 01:51:32,415
And I pick you up...

1118
01:51:32,585 --> 01:51:36,214
...and somehow you hardly weigh
anything. I can't explain it.

1119
01:51:40,493 --> 01:51:43,223
Leave it! We don't need it!

1120
01:51:45,298 --> 01:51:47,630
Water. I need water.

1121
01:51:50,937 --> 01:51:52,962
-Where are we going?
-The river.

1122
01:51:59,946 --> 01:52:02,437
And we have to take Glenville
to avoid traffic...

1123
01:52:02,615 --> 01:52:05,379
...because the damn church
people drive too slow.

1124
01:52:46,159 --> 01:52:51,426
And as we get close to the river...

1125
01:53:00,073 --> 01:53:02,268
He's here!

1126
01:53:02,575 --> 01:53:05,442
...we see that everybody
is already there.

1127
01:53:21,861 --> 01:53:23,453
And I mean...

1128
01:53:24,731 --> 01:53:25,993
...everyone.

1129
01:53:38,511 --> 01:53:41,207
It's unbelievable.

1130
01:53:41,748 --> 01:53:45,878
The story of my life.

1131
01:53:54,460 --> 01:53:57,395
The strange thing is, there's
not a sad face to be found.

1132
01:53:57,564 --> 01:54:00,124
Everyone is just so glad
to see you...

1133
01:54:01,234 --> 01:54:03,532
...and send you off right.

1134
01:54:03,703 --> 01:54:09,335
Goodbye, everybody!
Farewell! Adieu!

1135
01:54:20,687 --> 01:54:23,281
My girl in the river.

1136
01:55:34,827 --> 01:55:37,660
You become what you always were.

1137
01:55:39,299 --> 01:55:41,665
A very big fish.

1138
01:55:46,773 --> 01:55:49,105
And that's how it happens.

1139
01:55:50,677 --> 01:55:52,474
Yeah.

1140
01:55:54,948 --> 01:55:57,508
Exactly.

1141
01:56:39,592 --> 01:56:40,991
Mom?

1142
01:58:08,214 --> 01:58:11,445
The Lord is my shepherd,
I shall not be in want.

1143
01:58:11,617 --> 01:58:15,144
He makes me to lie down
in green pastures.

1144
01:58:15,321 --> 01:58:18,290
He leads me beside the quiet waters.

1145
01:58:18,458 --> 01:58:20,426
He restores my soul.

1146
01:58:20,593 --> 01:58:24,586
He guides me in the paths of
righteousness for his name's sake.

1147
01:58:25,231 --> 01:58:28,462
Yea, though I walk through
the valley of the shadow of death...

1148
01:58:28,634 --> 01:58:31,262
...I will fear no evil,
for you are with me.

1149
01:58:31,437 --> 01:58:35,771
Surely goodness and love will
follow me all the days of my life.

1150
01:59:22,755 --> 01:59:27,192
Have you ever heard a joke so many
times you've forgotten why it's funny?

1151
01:59:27,360 --> 01:59:31,456
And then you hear it again
and suddenly it's new.

1152
01:59:31,631 --> 01:59:34,794
You remember why you loved it
in the first place.

1153
01:59:36,636 --> 01:59:39,833
So he said he'll fight the giant
who was 1 5 feet tall!

1154
01:59:40,006 --> 01:59:43,442
-No way!
-Dad! That's right, isn't it?

1155
01:59:43,609 --> 01:59:44,940
Pretty much.

1156
01:59:45,111 --> 01:59:47,341
See? So he was a giant.

1157
01:59:47,513 --> 01:59:49,981
That was my father's final joke,
I guess.

1158
01:59:50,149 --> 01:59:56,088
A man tells his stories so many times
that he becomes the stories.

1159
01:59:57,523 --> 01:59:59,855
They live on after him.

1160
02:00:02,128 --> 02:00:05,495
And in that way,
he becomes immortal.

